@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "10. Deciding Between <article>, <section>, or <div> Elements";
}

<div class="container">
    <h1>@ViewData["Title"]</h1>

    <p>At times it becomes fairly difficult to decide which element – <code>&lt;article&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;section&gt;</code>, or <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> – is the best element for the job based on its semantic meaning. The trick here, as with every semantic decision, is to look at the content.</p>

    <p>Both the <code>&lt;article&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;section&gt;</code> elements contribute to a document's structure and help to outline a document. If the content is being grouped solely for styling purposes and doesn't provide value to the outline of a document, use the <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> element.</p>

    <ul>
        <li>If the content adds to the document outline and it can be independently redistributed or syndicated, use the <code>&lt;article&gt;</code> element.</li>
        <li>If the content adds to the document outline and represents a thematic group of content, use the <code>&lt;section&gt;</code> element.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="navigation-buttons">
        <a href="@Url.Action("SectionElement", "Frontend")" class="btn btn-outline-primary">← Section Element</a>
        <a href="@Url.Action("HeaderElement", "Frontend")" class="btn btn-primary">Header Element →</a>
    </div>
</div>

